---
import "../styles/global.css";

const ssrnUrl =
  "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=5984574";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Minimal Tolerance Theorem
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The formal statement, conditions and corollary of the Minimal Tolerance Theorem by Federico Rodrigo."
    />
  </head>

  <body>

    <header class="site-header">

      <a href="/" class="logo">
        The Theorem of Minimal Tolerance
      </a>

  <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
  <a href="/">Home</a>
  <a href="/theory">Theory</a>
  <a href="/theorem">Theorem</a>
  <a href="/book">Book</a>
  <a
    href={ssrnUrl}
    target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"
  >
    Paper
  </a>
</nav>

    </header>

    <main>

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE FORMAL STATEMENT
          </p>

          <h1>
            The Minimal Tolerance Theorem
          </h1>

          <p class="lead">
            The State may be tolerated only under an exceptionally
            narrow set of functional conditions and never as a morally
            legitimate or generally efficient institution.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            DEFINITION
          </p>

          <h2>
            The structural free-rider problem
          </h2>

          <p>
            A structural free-rider problem exists when individuals
            can receive the benefit of a good or service regardless
            of whether they contribute to its provision, weakening
            the incentives for voluntary participation.
          </p>

          <p>
            The theorem is not concerned with ordinary market
            imperfections, externalities or undesirable outcomes.
            It applies only where voluntary provision persistently
            collapses because of the incentive structure itself.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="theorem">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THREE CONDITIONS
          </p>

          <h2>
            All conditions must hold simultaneously
          </h2>

          <div class="theorem-conditions">

            <article>
              <span>01</span>

              <h3>
                Effective non-excludability
              </h3>

              <p>
                Individuals cannot be effectively excluded from
                receiving the relevant benefit.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <span>02</span>

              <h3>
                Relevant non-rivalry
              </h3>

              <p>
                One person receiving the benefit does not meaningfully
                reduce its availability to others.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <span>03</span>

              <h3>
                Persistent collapse of voluntary provision
              </h3>

              <p>
                Stable voluntary provision remains unviable and the
                collapse cannot be attributed to removable regulatory
                obstacles.
              </p>
            </article>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THEOREM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Formal statement
          </h2>

          <blockquote class="formal-statement">
            In a non-ideal world, where the State is morally
            illegitimate and exhibits structural functional failures,
            its tolerance may be justified strictly on functional
            grounds only in cases where a structural free-rider
            problem renders stable voluntary provision unviable,
            under an exceptionally high evidentiary standard, and only
            when non-intervention would generate greater harm than the
            marginal harm introduced by state coercion.
          </blockquote>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE BURDEN OF PROOF
          </p>

          <h2>
            No presumption. No analogical expansion.
          </h2>

          <p>
            The burden of proof lies entirely with those proposing
            intervention.
          </p>

          <p>
            No state action may be presumed justified merely because
            a collective problem exists, because a good is important,
            or because a voluntary result appears insufficient.
          </p>

          <p>
            The exception is narrow, functional and evidentiary. It
            cannot be generalized or extended by analogy.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            COROLLARY
          </p>

          <h2>
            The default remains non-intervention
          </h2>

          <blockquote class="formal-statement">
            Where no structural free-rider problem exists—or where
            viable voluntary mechanisms are available—state
            intervention lacks functional justification and must be
            presumed illegitimate by default.
          </blockquote>

          <p class="plain-language">
            Put plainly: where there is no structural free-rider
            problem, there is no State.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            VISUAL SUMMARY
          </p>

          <h2>
            The theorem at a glance
          </h2>

          <img
            src="/images/theorem.png"
            alt="Visual representation of the Minimal Tolerance Theorem"
            loading="lazy"
          />

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="ssrn">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            ORIGINAL RESEARCH
          </p>

          <h2>
            Read the complete paper
          </h2>

          <p>
            The SSRN preprint develops the moral, economic and
            institutional argument behind the theorem.
          </p>

          <a
            href={ssrnUrl}
            class="primary"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Open on SSRN
          </a>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <footer>

      <p>
        © 2026 Minimal Tolerance · Federico Rodrigo
      </p>

      <nav aria-label="Footer navigation">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <a href="/theorem">Theorem</a>
        <a href="/#book">Book</a>

        <a
          href={ssrnUrl}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          SSRN
        </a>
      </nav>

    </footer>

  </body>

</html>
